[1]
Date: Wed 8 Sep 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Arab News, 7 Sep 2004 [edited]
<http://arabnews.com/?page=1Â§ion=0&article=51118&d=7&m=9&y=2004>


RVF reported in Jizan; livestock owners warned
------------------------------------------------------------
Agriculture Minister Dr. Fahd Balghaneim has called on livestock
owners and breeders in the southern Jizan region to take
precautionary measures against Rift Valley Fever, after reports
that 5 animals in the region had tested positive for the deadly virus.

The minister, however, downplayed the new RVF outbreak, saying
that there was only "a limited activity of the virus" in the region. His
ministry was implementing a comprehensive plan to deal with the
situation and prevent the spread of the disease.

The Agriculture Ministry discovered 5 positive samples of the virus -
- 4 in Abu Areesh and one in Aaridah -- during periodic
examinations, the Saudi Press Agency said, quoting the minister.
"These positive results from the tests do not mean that the
situation in the region has reached epidemic proportions,"
Balghaneim said. [The correct word to use, when only animals are
involved, is "epizootic". - Mod.JW]

The RVF outbreak in Jizan 3 years ago killed more than 125
people. In April of this year [2004], the ministry lifted a 3-year-old
ban on the movement of livestock between regions hit by the virus.
The authorities agreed to lift the ban in light of a ministerial
committee report that said that the campaign to contain the disease
had been successful. "The situation is now stable, as no RVF viral
activity has been found in humans, animals, or mosquitoes,"
Balghaneim said, when the ban was lifted.

The minister urged the authorities to be cautious about the RVF
virus, which is capable of surviving in the eggs of mosquitoes for a
long time, and, can surface whenever it finds a hospitable
environment.

The Agriculture Ministry has set up an early warning unit to monitor
and contain infectious diseases affecting agricultural and animal
resources in certain regions, before they spread to other parts of
the Kingdom. The ministry also established a laboratory in Jizan to
carry out medical tests and check the effectiveness of insecticides.

RVF primarily affects animals, but, occasionally, causes illness and
leads to high morbidity and mortality in humans. According to the
World Health Organization, many different species of mosquitoes
are vectors for the RVF virus.

[Byline: P.K. Abdul Ghafour]

