Date: Wed 8 Sep 2004
From: Shamsudeen Fagbo <oloungbo@yahoo.com>


Comment Re. Rift Valley fever - Saudi Arabia (Jizan): suspected
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The [Saudi] Ministry of Agriculture must be commended for
detecting and reporting animal cases before detection in human
subjects. This was not the case during the 2000 outbreak. I hope
that more details will soon be provided. Helpful details would include
the types of tests employed (probably ELISA), the total number of
animals tested, the species tested, and mosquitoes spp. tested. No
details could be found on the Ministry's web-site:
<http://www.agrwat.gov.sa/index.php?newlang=english>.
The spread of the virus can be evaluated only if more data are
provided.

However, the recurrence of RVF in Jizan is not surprising.
Expectations of new RVF cases, due to floods and altered ecology,
have been discussed before (see ProMED posts 20031016.2612
and 20031016.2606). There have been severe floods in Jizan, and
other parts of South Western Saudi Arabia, with loss of life,
livestock, and infrastructure, in April and August 2004.

As regards the intended surveillance, this outbreak reinforces the
fact that surveillance should be more widespread and of a
permanent nature. The possibility of potentially exposed vacation-
goers returning to other parts of the country is present, and these
people may not be covered by geographically-restricted
surveillance.

Additionally, surveillance will not be fully effective unless
awareness of the differential diagnosis of RVF is not practically
applied. Other zoonoses/diseases such as brucellosis, Q fever,
and malaria should be factored into a nationwide surveillance. This
was not the case during the 2000 outbreak [see Fagbo SF. Rift
Valley fever epidemic in Saudi Arabia: disconcerting
epidemiological defects and lack of differential diagnoses and
concordance in studies. Clin. Infect. Dis. 2004 May
15;38(10):1503].

Some of the figures and lay statements from the Saudi Gazette
news wire definitely do not help to put things in perspective. For
example, to date, there has been no scientific proof to justify the
claim that the "virus had reached the Kingdom from Africa through
infected sheep and was passed on by mosquitoes." In the article,
"livestock breeders" seems to be an inaccurate translation from
the Arabic original, a government press release. I think "livestock
owners" was intended.

The recent reports of active dengue transmission in the Jeddah
area lead to worries about the presence of potential RVF
transmitting mosquitoes in this vital area. Monitoring and
surveillance in this area should also be enhanced.

--
Shamsudeen Fagbo,DVM
<oloungbo@yahoo.com>

[We are most grateful to Dr. Fagbo for these important comments
which include scientifically-based, first-hand information. - Mod. AS].
